{"type":null,"faqId":26428,"title":"Ten Tips for Taking Photos with Your Phone","answer":"<p>\n<p style=\"margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-size:10.5pt;font-family:'Calibri','sans-serif';text-align:center\" align=\"center\"><b><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman','serif';\ncolor:#333333\">Ten Tips for Taking Photos with Your Phone</span></b></p>\n<p style=\"margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-size:10.5pt;font-family:'Calibri','sans-serif';text-align:center\" align=\"center\">&nbsp;</p>\n<p style=\"margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-size:10.5pt;font-family:'Calibri','sans-serif';text-align:left\" align=\"left\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman','serif';\">There are\nsome skills you need to grasp regarding taking photos with your phone. </span></p>\n<p style=\"margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-size:10.5pt;font-family:'Calibri','sans-serif';text-align:left;\" align=\"left\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman','serif';\ncolor:#333333;\">Make sure you and your phone are equipped\nwith the following: </span></p>\n<p style=\"margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-size:10.5pt;font-family:'Calibri','sans-serif';text-align:left;\" align=\"left\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman','serif';\ncolor:#333333;\">1. Resolution of 5 MP or above</span></p>\n<p style=\"margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-size:10.5pt;font-family:'Calibri','sans-serif';text-align:left;\" align=\"left\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman','serif';\ncolor:#333333;\">2. Flash and different shooting modes, such\nas night mode</span></p>\n<p style=\"margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-size:10.5pt;font-family:'Calibri','sans-serif';text-align:left;\" align=\"left\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman','serif';\ncolor:#333333;\">3. Basic applications for processing images</span></p>\n<p style=\"margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-size:10.5pt;font-family:'Calibri','sans-serif';text-align:left;\" align=\"left\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman','serif';\ncolor:#333333;\">4. Sufficient battery power (because photo\nshooting incurs high power consumption)</span></p>\n<p style=\"margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-size:10.5pt;font-family:'Calibri','sans-serif';text-align:left;\" align=\"left\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman','serif';\ncolor:#333333;\">5. Basic aesthetic knowledge (sense of\nbeauty)</span></p>\n<p style=\"margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-size:10.5pt;font-family:'Calibri','sans-serif';text-align:left;\" align=\"left\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman','serif';\ncolor:#333333;\">6. Good patience (may be required when you\nwant to take stunning photos)</span></p>\n<p style=\"margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-size:10.5pt;font-family:'Calibri','sans-serif';text-align:left\" align=\"left\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman','serif';color:#333333;\">7. (Optional) Macro lens</span></p>\n<p style=\"margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-size:10.5pt;font-family:'Calibri','sans-serif';text-align:left;\" align=\"left\"><b><span style=\"\nfont-family:'Times New Roman','serif';color:#333333;\">Ten\ntips for taking photos</span></b></p>\n<p style=\"margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-size:10.5pt;font-family:'Calibri','sans-serif';text-align:left;\" align=\"left\"><b><span style=\"\nfont-family:'Times New Roman','serif';color:#333333;\">1.\nMake sure your hands do not shake.</span></b></p>\n<p style=\"margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-size:10.5pt;font-family:'Calibri','sans-serif';text-align:left;\" align=\"left\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman','serif';\ncolor:#333333;\">The first thing you need to learn is to\nkeep your hands steady so that the photos are not blurred. It is recommended\nthat you hold the phone with both hands. </span></p>\n<p style=\"margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-size:10.5pt;font-family:'Calibri','sans-serif';text-align:left;\" align=\"left\">&nbsp;</p>\n<p style=\"margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-size:10.5pt;font-family:'Calibri','sans-serif';text-align:left;\" align=\"left\"><b><span style=\"\nfont-family:'Times New Roman','serif';color:#333333;\">2.\nPress and hold the shutter bound for 3 seconds. </span></b></p>\n<p style=\"margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-size:10.5pt;font-family:'Calibri','sans-serif';text-align:left;\" align=\"left\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman','serif';\ncolor:#333333;\">You may have found that your phone's\nshutter is different from that of the camera. Cameras' shutter is triggered\nwithin 1 second (unless the shutter speed is adjusted). After your phone's\nshutter is pressed, the phone CPU needs some time to send the shooting command\nto the shutter. If you release the shutter too soon or not firmly enough, the\nphoto may be blurred. Therefore, you are advised to press and hold the shutter\nfor three seconds when taking photos.</span></p>\n<p style=\"margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-size:10.5pt;font-family:'Calibri','sans-serif';text-align:left;\" align=\"left\">&nbsp;</p>\n<p style=\"margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-size:10.5pt;font-family:'Calibri','sans-serif';text-align:left;\" align=\"left\"><b><span style=\"\nfont-family:'Times New Roman','serif';color:#333333;\">3.\nMake use of the light. </span></b></p>\n<p style=\"margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-size:10.5pt;font-family:'Calibri','sans-serif';text-align:left\" align=\"left\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman','serif';color:#333333;\">You can try taking photos in different light conditions. If the light is\ninsufficient, turn on the flash or night mode. You can also turn off the flash\nfor special effects, which requires more time and attempts. You can achieve\ndifferent effects by adjusting the brightness on your phone. </span></p>\n<p style=\"margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-size:10.5pt;font-family:'Calibri','sans-serif';text-align:left\" align=\"left\">&nbsp;</p>\n<p style=\"margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-size:10.5pt;font-family:'Calibri','sans-serif';text-align:left;\" align=\"left\"><b><span style=\"\nfont-family:'Times New Roman','serif';color:#333333;\">4.\nSet the photo scene properly. </span></b></p>\n<p style=\"margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-size:10.5pt;font-family:'Calibri','sans-serif';text-align:left;\" align=\"left\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman','serif';\ncolor:#333333;\">Apart from light, you have to handle the\nscene for the photo well. Photo scenarios are usually classified into panorama\nand close-up. When you take a panoramic photo, stand in a place with an open\nview. When you take a close-up photo, control the light properly. </span></p>\n<p style=\"margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-size:10.5pt;font-family:'Calibri','sans-serif';text-align:left;\" align=\"left\">&nbsp;</p>\n<p style=\"margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-size:10.5pt;font-family:'Calibri','sans-serif';text-align:left;\" align=\"left\"><b><span style=\"\nfont-family:'Times New Roman','serif';color:#333333;\">5.\nTake photos in side light. </span></b></p>\n<p style=\"margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-size:10.5pt;font-family:'Calibri','sans-serif';text-align:left;\" align=\"left\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman','serif';\ncolor:#333333;\">Stand in the direction of the light and\ntake photos of objects and people under the light. For example, the light\nrefraction in sunset. You can also ask the model to stand in the sun and take\nphoto from his or her shadow. This is called shadow backlight shooting. </span></p>\n<p style=\"margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-size:10.5pt;font-family:'Calibri','sans-serif';text-align:left;\" align=\"left\">&nbsp;</p>\n<p style=\"margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-size:10.5pt;font-family:'Calibri','sans-serif';text-align:left;\" align=\"left\"><b><span style=\"\nfont-family:'Times New Roman','serif';color:#333333;\">6.\nStay close to the object you are shooting. </span></b></p>\n<p style=\"margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-size:10.5pt;font-family:'Calibri','sans-serif';text-align:left;\" align=\"left\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman','serif';\ncolor:#333333;\">Common phones do not support adjusting the\nfocal length. When you shoot portraits from a long distance, the photos will be\nblurred. (This does not apply to scenery, which requires far focusing.) The\nbest distance to the shooting object is 1</span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman','serif'\">â€“2 feet.</span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman','serif';\ncolor:#333333;\"> </span></p>\n<p style=\"margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-size:10.5pt;font-family:'Calibri','sans-serif';text-align:left;\" align=\"left\">&nbsp;</p>\n<p style=\"margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-size:10.5pt;font-family:'Calibri','sans-serif';text-align:left;\" align=\"left\"><b><span style=\"\nfont-family:'Times New Roman','serif';color:#333333;\">7. Use\nthe golden mapping method.</span></b></p>\n<p style=\"margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-size:10.5pt;font-family:'Calibri','sans-serif';text-align:left;\" align=\"left\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman','serif';\ncolor:#333333;\">Golden mapping provides the best split\npoint in aesthetics. Instead of being at the center of the viewfinder, the\nmodel should stay slightly to the left to form a better image. </span></p>\n<p style=\"margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-size:10.5pt;font-family:'Calibri','sans-serif';text-align:left;\" align=\"left\">&nbsp;</p>\n<p style=\"margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-size:10.5pt;font-family:'Calibri','sans-serif';text-align:left;\" align=\"left\"><b><span style=\"\nfont-family:'Times New Roman','serif';color:#333333;\">8.\nShoot from the horizontal angle. </span></b></p>\n<p style=\"margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-size:10.5pt;font-family:'Calibri','sans-serif';text-align:left;\" align=\"left\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman','serif';\ncolor:#333333;\">Keep your eye, the camera lens, and the\nmodel's eyes on the same level. For example, you can use this method when\ncapturing a certain expression in one's eyes or a facial expression. You can\nlower the shooting angle to shoot the model's feet to present a special work. </span></p>\n<p style=\"margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-size:10.5pt;font-family:'Calibri','sans-serif';text-align:left;\" align=\"left\">&nbsp;</p>\n<p style=\"margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-size:10.5pt;font-family:'Calibri','sans-serif';text-align:left;\" align=\"left\"><b><span style=\"\nfont-family:'Times New Roman','serif';color:#333333;\">9.\nTake advantage of the background. </span></b></p>\n<p style=\"margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-size:10.5pt;font-family:'Calibri','sans-serif';text-align:left;\" align=\"left\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman','serif';\ncolor:#333333;\">The application of background is applicable\nto all shooting techniques. You can emphasize a certain part on the model or\nmake a certain one in the background outstand using the model. </span></p>\n<p style=\"margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-size:10.5pt;font-family:'Calibri','sans-serif';text-align:left;\" align=\"left\">&nbsp;</p>\n<p style=\"margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-size:10.5pt;font-family:'Calibri','sans-serif';text-align:left;\" align=\"left\"><b><span style=\"\nfont-family:'Times New Roman','serif';color:#333333;\">10.\nInstall color adjusting applications on your phone. </span></b></p>\n<p style=\"margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-size:10.5pt;font-family:'Calibri','sans-serif';text-align:left\" align=\"left\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman','serif';color:#333333;\">Even photos taken by professional photographers require color adjustment.\nUsing color adjusting applications help beautify your works and make them\nunique. You can adjust the colors for your photos the way you like.</span></p>\n<br>\n</p>","faqTypeId":null,"faqType":null,"useful":0,"unUseful":0,"languageId":1,"languageName":"en","faqCode":"827","faqTypeCode":null,"isTop":"0","moduleCode":"faq","productId":null,"productCode":null,"postDate":1433165309000,"seriesProductName":"","visitedTimes":17,"isUsefulFlag":null,"score":0,"times":0,"imageList":null,"displayType":"text","justView":"0","fileName":null,"filePath":null,"imagePath":null,"imageName":null,"productIdList":null,"curPage":null,"pageSize":null,"siteCode":null,"statusFlag":"Publish","returnCode":0,"totalRows":null,"keywords":"Ten Tips for Taking Photos with Your Phone","avgScore":0.0,"createDate":null,"totalPages":null}